Philanthropic Advisory Service 


At Hillview, we engage our clients in value-based conversations about philanthropy early on in our relationship. This is to clearly understand their intentions, assess all available options, analyze the benefits and potentials of each element, and finally create a custom-tailored plan that addresses their specific needs.
Philanthropic objectives are becoming increasingly important to both individuals and families who are looking for a cohesive strategy to reach their goals and leave a lasting legacy.


For almost two decades, Hillview has been a trusted provider of financial advisory services, with access to leading edge philanthropic knowledge and resources from the industry’s innovators. Our primary objective is to ensure each client’s charitable activity has the desired impact on the causes that interest them the most, but more importantly, that in the end our clients have a means to achieve their philanthropic aspirations.
We have a full suite of philanthropic services including strategic planning, asset management, administrative and advisory services.












We work closely with you to provide:


PHILANTHROPIC ADVISORY SERVICES

– Philanthropic Asset Management
– Philanthropic Strategic Planning
– Guidance on Vehicle Selection (Private Foundations vs. Donor Advised Funds)
– Integration of Charitable Aspirations in Legacy and Estate Planning





– Peer‐based Perspectives on Multigenerational Philanthropy
– Annual Charitable Gift Planning
– Consultation on Socially Responsible and Impact Investments













Case studies 




Family Foundation vs. Donor Advised Fund




Estate Planning




Socially Responsible Investment Portfolio








A second-generation member of a wealthy family stewarded her family’s private foundation which served as their primary giving vehicle for over a decade. The family began to realize that the foundation’s management and administrative costs were an increasing burden and wanted to explore alternative options.  Hillview conducted a detailed cost/benefit comparison of the private foundation and donor-advised fund models.


This assessment took into account the overall management requirements, administrative expenses, and payout requirements associated with each option.  We also confirmed that each option would provide sufficient flexibility in how she executed the family’s giving strategies. After extensive consultation with family members Hillview recommended that they establish a donor advised fund as a highly cost-effective solution requiring minimal changes to the family’s philanthropic aspirations.








Prompted by a client’s request to comment on his and his wife’s life insurance, Hillview assessed the policies’ role with respect to the family’s income replacement needs and wealth transfer objectives.  In the course of our consultation, Hillview found that the client was “over-insured” and that his wife’s policy was both costly and misaligned with the family’s needs.  More importantly, we uncovered several material shortcomings with the family’s estate plans.  These red flags indicated the need for a comprehensive and coordinated estate planning assessment and design.  Hillview assumed the role of quarterbacking a team-oriented approach involving the client’s life insurance professional, T&E attorney, and accountant.


The outcome of our work was: 1) an updated estate plan aligned with the client’s wealth preservation and transfer goals; 2) establishment of revocable trusts to avoid probate and to maintain family’s privacy; 3) replacement of existing life insurance with more suitable policies that had preferential pricing and flexible terms; 4) increased and segregated funding for the children’s educational expenses. The most significant outcome, however, was our client’s expressed “peace of mind” that his wealth will transfer, upon his passing, in a manner that provides for long-term financial security for his family.








Our client was interested in aligning her investments with her values and asked us for guidance. She completed a survey to establish socially responsible investment (SRI) screens. After several consultations, a prototype portfolio was designed using both positive and negative screening methodologies, while targeting a risk/return profile aligned with her custom benchmark. The prototype SRI portfolio was benchmarked against a custom global benchmark – 80% S&P 500 Index + 20% S&P ADR Index.


The recommended portfolio excluded oil, gas and coal companies that are major suppliers of fossil fuels and companies that facilitate the production and transportation of fossil fuels. Major chemical companies, tobacco companies, weapons manufacturers and nuclear power generators were among the exclusions beyond the fossil fuel universe. The portfolio also favored companies that receive high scores in an environmental, social and governance ranking system, with emphasis placed on companies that contribute to improving the sustainability of the global economy.


































